The cult of the '''Heliopolitan Triad''' was [[Canaanite religion|Canaanite]] in essence but the [[Ancient Rome|Romans]] adopted it when they conquered the city of [[Heliopolis (Syria)|Heliopolis]] (modern [[Baalbeck]]) in the [[Beqaa Valley]] of [[Lebanon]]. The Canaanite god [[Baʿal]] ([[Hadad]]) [[interpretatio graeca|was equated with]] [[Jupiter Heliopolitanus]], [[Astarte]] or [[Atargatis]] with [[Venus Heliopolitana]] and [[Adon]], the god of spring, with [[Mercury (god)|Mercury]].<ref>[http://www.tourisminlebanon.com/baalbak.asp Tourism in Lebanon<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The Romans built magnificent temples for the Heliopolitan Triad in Heliopolis. Votives dedicated to the cult were also found in the village of [[Bechouat]] in Lebanon.

